  <datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">William Lloyd Garrison tells of his greatly delayed journey and his arrival at Lydia Mott&apos;s home. Garrison thought that he had arrived too late to speak at the meeting. At the insistence of the audience, William H. Topp, a black friend, conveyed Garrison in a sleigh to Respresentative Hall. Garrison lectured to an attentive audience, but not to his own satisfaction, &quot;for everything was in a whirl with me. But the kindness and patience of the audience were wonderful.&quot; Garrison says: &quot;To-night, Sunday, I am to lecture in a fine hall---the weather is pleasant---and I hope we shall have a good audience.&quot;</subfield>
